{"id":"1405.5180","submitter":"Jerrold Franklin","authors":"Jerrold Franklin","title":"The 'Sears paradox'","comments":"9 pages, 2figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We resolve a paradox in special relativity proposed by F. W. Sears for the\naction of forces on a rigid body. In the paradox, a moving rigid rod is struck\nat different times by impulsive forces, but continues to move with unchanged\nvelocity, with the forces having no effect. Our conclusion is that the usual\nlaws of mechanics can be applied to a rigid body only in its rest system\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 16 Feb 2014 16:13:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-05-21"}
